```

The current LicenseView (UI/LicenseView.swift) has two separate error display sections: one for `runtimeIntegrityFailure` (orange warning) and one for `activationError ?? licenseStore.lastError` (red error). The styling (background, stroke, icon) is nearly identical except for colors and icons. To reduce duplication, you can create a computed property that returns a single optional error with a type (warning vs. error) and message. For example:

```swift
private var displayError: (message: String, isWarning: Bool)? {
    if let integrityFailure = licenseStore.runtimeIntegrityFailure {
        return (integrityFailure, isWarning: true)
    }
    if let error = activationError ?? licenseStore.lastError {
        return (error, isWarning: false)
    }
    return nil
}
```

Then in the body, use a single conditional block:

```swift
if let error = displayError {
    HStack(alignment: .top, spacing: 12) {
        Image(systemName: error.isWarning ? "exclamationmark.shield.fill" : "exclamationmark.triangle.fill")
            .foregroundStyle(error.isWarning ? .orange : .red)
        VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 4) {
            Text(error.isWarning ? "Licensing disabled for this session" : "Activation Failed")
                .font(.headline)
                .foregroundStyle(.primary)
            Text(error.message)
                .font(.callout)
                .foregroundStyle(.secondary)
            if error.isWarning {
                Text("Install a valid signed build before activating a license or starting a trial.")
                    .font(.callout)
                    .foregroundStyle(.secondary)
            }
        }
        Spacer(minLength: 0)
    }
    .padding(16)
    .frame(maxWidth: 340)
    .background(
        RoundedRectangle(cornerRadius: 12, style: .continuous)
            .fill(error.isWarning ? Color.orange.opacity(0.12) : Color.red.opacity(0.08))
    )
    .overlay(
        RoundedRectangle(cornerRadius: 12, style: .continuous)
            .stroke(error.isWarning ? Color.orange.opacity(0.5) : Color.red.opacity(0.3), lineWidth: 1)
    )
}
```

This eliminates the duplicated layout and styling code. You would remove the separate orange block at the top and the red block at the bottom. Note that the warning block previously appeared at the very top of the VStack, so you may want to keep this consolidated block in the same position (e.g., as the first element) to maintain visual hierarchy. The refactor reduces code duplication, improves maintainability, and makes it easier to adjust error styling in one place.

