`saveDiagnostics(capture:dependencies:)` is an `async` static function with no actor annotation, so it runs on the cooperative thread pool — not the main actor. However, `DictationDiagnosticsDependencies` holds references to `SettingsStore`, `ModelManager`, and `VocabularyMinerStore`, which are `@MainActor`-isolated types in TunedVoice. Accessing their properties from an off-actor async context would be a Swift concurrency violation caught at compile time.

`await MainActor.run { ... }` hops to the main actor for the duration of the closure, reads all the needed properties, and returns a plain tuple of value types (`String`, `Bool`, `Int`, `[WeightedTerm]`, etc.). Once the closure returns, those values are safe to use on any thread because they are value-type copies, not references to actor-isolated state.

The pattern batches all main-actor reads into a single hop:
```swift
let settings = await MainActor.run {
    let vocabularyBoostEnabled = dependencies.settingsStore.ctcBoostingMode == .on
    let weightedTerms = CustomVocabularyStore.allWeightedVocabularyTerms(...)
    return (...)
}
```
This is intentionally efficient — one context switch for all settings instead of multiple `await` hops. After this block, the rest of `saveDiagnostics` — JSON encoding, encryption, and file I/O — runs off the main actor, keeping the UI thread unblocked during potentially slow disk and crypto operations.

