`UI/VocabularySettingsView.swift` holds two `@State` ViewModels:
```swift
@State private var wordsVM = CustomWordsViewModel()
@State private var replacementsVM = ReplacementsViewModel()
```
The separation reflects a single-responsibility split: `CustomWordsViewModel` owns the raw vocabulary word list (words sent to the CTC model's boost vocabulary), while `ReplacementsViewModel` owns text replacement rules (the post-transcription find/replace patterns stored as `TextReplacer.Replacement`). These are logically related but architecturally distinct — the CTC boost and text replacement are separate subsystems, and keeping their ViewModels separate means each can be persisted, validated, and tested independently.

`allEntries`, referenced in `ForEach(allEntries)` and the empty-state guard `if allEntries.isEmpty`, is a computed property that merges both ViewModels into a unified `[VocabEntry]` list. Each `VocabEntry` carries its `word` and an array of `replacements: [String]`, which is why the row renderer conditionally shows:
```swift
if !entry.replacements.isEmpty {
    Text("replaces \(entry.replacements.map { ""\($0)"" }.joined(separator: ", "))")
}
