After `MiningPipelineRunner.runLocalBatch` succeeds, the coordinator posts:
```swift
NotificationCenter.default.post(name: .tunedVoiceVocabularyChanged, object: nil)
```
The comment in `VocabularyMiningCoordinator` explains exactly why: `run_mining.py` writes new terms directly to `custom_vocabulary.json` on disk. This bypasses `CustomVocabularyStore.saveWeighted()` — the normal in-process save path that would already trigger a UI refresh through `CustomVocabularyStore`'s own change notification.

Without the manual notification post, the vocabulary UI would be stale: the JSON file on disk would contain new mined terms, but the in-memory `CustomVocabularyStore` wouldn't know to reload, so users would see no change until app restart.

The notification is posted inside the `runLocalBatch` completion closure on `MainActor`:
```swift
await MainActor.run {
    capturedRunner?.runLocalBatch(entries: entries) { succeeded in
        if succeeded {
            Task { await capturedAccumulator.clearAll() }
            NotificationCenter.default.post(name: .tunedVoiceVocabularyChanged, object: nil)
        }
    }
}
```
Note the `capturedRunner` and `capturedAccumulator` captures — `self` is a `struct` so it can't be captured directly in the closure. The coordinator captures the specific dependencies it needs by value before the `MainActor.run` hop, which is the correct pattern for value-type coordinators that bridge into closure-based async callbacks.

If you add a new code path that writes to `custom_vocabulary.json` outside of `CustomVocabularyStore`, you must also post `.tunedVoiceVocabularyChanged` or the UI will be stale.

