`SettingsStore` in `Services/Settings/SettingsStore.swift` implements a facade-with-delegation pattern. The class owns five typed subsystem objects — `general: GeneralSettings`, `hotkeys: HotkeySettings`, `recording: RecordingSettings`, `transcription: TranscriptionSettings`, and `mining: MiningSettings` — each responsible for its own domain and persistence logic.

The store then exposes flattened computed properties that forward reads and writes to the appropriate subsystem. For example:

```swift
var chunkingStrategy: ChunkingStrategyOption {
    get { transcription.chunkingStrategy }
    set { transcription.chunkingStrategy = newValue }
}
```

Callers (SwiftUI views, the transcription engine) never need to know that `ChunkingStrategyOption` lives inside `TranscriptionSettings`. They write `settingsStore.chunkingStrategy = .vad` and the delegation is invisible.

This design has a critical interaction with `@Observable`: the macro tracks observations at the property-access level through the call chain. When a view reads `settingsStore.vadSilenceThreshold`, the observation system registers a dependency on `transcription.vadSilenceThreshold` inside the getter. A subsequent mutation to `recording.saveRecordingsEnabled` does not invalidate that view — only views that read `saveRecordingsEnabled` re-render. This is why the subsystem split pays off: it enables `@Observable`'s fine-grained tracking to work correctly across the entire settings surface without any manual `objectWillChange` calls.

The private `storage: SettingsStorage` is marked `@ObservationIgnored` precisely because it should never be part of this observation graph — it is a persistence backend, not a UI-driving property.

