```

`EngineRouter` conforms to both `TranscriptionEngine` and `@unchecked Sendable`, which means it must cross actor isolation boundaries safely without itself being an actor. Marking it `@unchecked Sendable` shifts thread-safety responsibility to the class author. Making it a full actor would change reference semantics and force every caller to `await` even synchronous properties like `state` and `loadedModelID` — an unnecessary cost since only one piece of state is ever mutated.

The only mutable state is `lastUsedOption`, a diagnostic field that records which engine handled the last transcription. A single `OSAllocatedUnfairLock` covers it:

```swift
private let _lastUsedLock = OSAllocatedUnfairLock(initialState: TranscriptionEngineOption.parakeet)
var lastUsedOption: TranscriptionEngineOption {
    get { _lastUsedLock.withLock { $0 } }
}
```

Writes happen exactly once per transcription in `transcribe(_:)`: `_lastUsedLock.withLock { $0 = .parakeet }`. `OSAllocatedUnfairLock` is preferred over `NSLock` or a serial `DispatchQueue` because it has near-zero overhead when uncontested — the common case here, since `lastUsedOption` is only written at the start of each transcription and is not a hot path. This pattern keeps all async work in Swift Concurrency (the `async throws` methods use `await` throughout) while protecting the one shared mutable field with the minimum viable primitive.

