The `periodicTask` in `startStreaming(modelID:)` of `Services/Transcription/ParakeetStreamingService.swift` runs a tight loop:
```swift
periodicTask = Task { [weak self] in
    guard let self else { return }
    while !Task.isCancelled {
        await self.runStreamingPass()
        await Task.yield()
    }
}
```
There is no `Task.sleep`, no timer, and no minimum interval. Instead, `runStreamingPass()` itself is the throttle: because Parakeet takes ~20ms per second of audio and `accumulatedSamples` grows continuously, each successive pass takes proportionally longer. At 5 seconds of audio, a pass takes ~100ms. At 30 seconds, ~600ms. The pass frequency naturally decreases as recording length increases — exactly when lower update frequency is acceptable to the user.

`Task.yield()` after each pass is the only cooperative scheduling point. It allows audio capture callbacks (feeding `feedAudio(_:)`) and UI updates to run between passes, preventing the inference loop from monopolizing the actor.

The implication is that short recordings get high-frequency updates (many passes per second) while long recordings near `maxStreamingSamples` (240,000 samples = 15s at 16kHz) get low-frequency updates — but by that point the `finalUsesChunkProcessor` path in `finishStreaming()` takes over. System load is bounded because only one inference runs at a time (no parallelism), but the CPU stays continuously busy during recording. The `streamingPassesEnabled` UserDefaults flag (`streamingPassesDisabled` key) exists precisely to disable this loop on slower devices.

