The root cause is stale cache. `availablePacks()` in `VocabularyPackStore.swift` writes results into `private static var _cachedPacks` on first load and short-circuits on every subsequent call: `if let cached = _cachedPacks { return cached }`. If the cache is not cleared when the source directory changes, callers always see the first load regardless of the current `_directoryOverride`.

The production guard is the `didSet` observer on `_directoryOverride`:
```swift
internal static var _directoryOverride: URL? {
    didSet { _cachedPacks = nil }
}
```
Every assignment to `_directoryOverride` — including assignments to `nil` — triggers `didSet`, which sets `_cachedPacks = nil`. The next call to `availablePacks()` finds no cached value, falls into the full load path, and picks up whichever directory `_directoryOverride` now points to.

The bug in the test scenario means `_directoryOverride` was likely set via direct mutation of the backing storage rather than through the property setter, bypassing `didSet`. In Swift, `didSet` only fires when the value is written through the declared property; if a test somehow bypasses that (e.g., using a pointer or a different code path that does not go through the property), the observer never fires. The fix is to always assign through the property: `VocabularyPackStore._directoryOverride = secondFixtureURL` — this triggers `didSet`, clears `_cachedPacks`, and forces a fresh load.

