The `completedKey` flag in `BulkMiningRecovery` is not tracking whether the batch *succeeded* — it is tracking whether the recovery *attempted* to feed historical data into the system. The comment above the final `UserDefaults.standard.set(true, forKey: completedKey)` call explains this directly:

> Mark as completed regardless of batch outcome — the transcripts are in the accumulator and will be picked up by normal mining flow if the batch fails.

Once `BulkMiningRecovery.runIfNeeded` has iterated all the `.diagnostics.json` files and called `miningAccumulator.add(text:)` for each extracted transcript, the data is durably queued in the `MiningAccumulator`. Re-running the recovery on the next launch would redundantly re-read and re-add the same historical transcripts, bloating the accumulator and potentially double-counting vocabulary frequency signals.

The design intentionally separates two concerns: *ingestion* (feeding old transcripts into the accumulator, which `BulkMiningRecovery` does once) and *processing* (running the batch, which the normal mining flow handles on retries). The `runLocalBatch` completion closure in `miningPipelineRunner` only clears the accumulator on success:

```swift
miningPipelineRunner.runLocalBatch(entries: entries) { succeeded in
    if succeeded {
        Task { await capturedAccumulator.clearAll() }
        NotificationCenter.default.post(name: .tunedVoiceVocabularyChanged, object: nil)
    } else {
        Log.mining.warning("BulkMiningRecovery: batch failed — transcripts preserved for retry via normal mining flow")
    }
}
```

If the batch fails, transcripts stay in the accumulator for the normal pipeline to pick up later. Marking `completedKey` true ensures recovery does not re-run and re-add the same transcripts a second time, which would corrupt the accumulator state.

