The guard at the top of `microphoneStatus()` in `Services/Permissions/PermissionManager.swift` exists to support end-to-end UI test runs where you cannot programmatically grant or deny real system permissions:

```swift
if AppEnvironment.current?.isE2EMode == true,
   AppEnvironment.current?.denyMicrophoneE2E == true {
    return .denied
}
```

During an E2E test, `AppEnvironment.current` is populated from launch arguments or environment variables injected by the test runner. When `isE2EMode` is true and `denyMicrophoneE2E` is true, the method short-circuits and returns `.denied` without consulting `AVCaptureDevice`, simulating the experience a real user would have if they had previously declined the microphone prompt.

Without this escape hatch, an E2E test scenario covering the 'microphone denied' UI path would require physically revoking the app's microphone permission in System Settings before each run — a step that cannot be automated in CI. The dual-flag design (`isE2EMode` AND `denyMicrophoneE2E`) means E2E mode by itself does not automatically deny the mic; the second flag must be set explicitly, so tests that want a granted microphone state can run in E2E mode without interference.

If you observe `microphoneGranted` stuck at `false` in automated test runs when you expect it to be `true`, check whether `denyMicrophoneE2E` is being accidentally passed as a launch argument.

