The drain sleep in `Services/Audio/AudioRecorder.swift:stopCapture()` addresses issue #748: truncation of the last word in a dictation session.

The root cause is the threading model of `AVAudioEngine`'s tap. The tap installed via `installTap(on:inputFormat:converter:generation:)` fires on a non-`@MainActor` background thread. Buffers are marshalled back to the `@MainActor`-isolated `AudioRecorder` via an asynchronous `Task { @MainActor in self.appendBuffer(...) }` hop. This hop is not guaranteed to land before `stopCapture()` returns.

When the user releases the hotkey, `stopCapture()` runs on `@MainActor`. If the code immediately bumped `engineGeneration` to gate out the tap, the ~85 ms HAL buffer already in-flight (tap fired, `@MainActor` hop not yet delivered) would be rejected by the generation check — silently dropping the last word.

The fix:
```swift
do {
    try await Task.sleep(for: TunedVoiceConstants.stopCaptureDrainDelay)
} catch {
    Log.audio.info("stopCapture drain sleep cancelled — finalising immediately")
}
```

Sleeping gives the in-flight `@MainActor` hops time to land. `buffersArrivedDuringDrain` (difference of `bufferCountAfterDrain - bufferCountAtStop`) is logged for observability into how effective the drain window is.

The `do/catch` (not `try?`) is a Hard Rule in the codebase. A real `Task` cancellation must still fall through to bump generation and finalize — using `try?` would swallow the cancellation signal and potentially leave the engine running. The `catch` branch logs and proceeds, ensuring cleanup always completes regardless of cancellation.

